  "prompt": "Why the colour of wires in homes are black, green and red?",
  "response": "The color coding of electrical wires is standardized to ensure safety and proper identification in installations. In many countries, including the United States and those that follow the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) guidelines, these colors generally have specific meanings:\n\n1. **Black**: This is typically used for hot wires. Hot wires carry the current from the power source to the load (like outlets, switches, and fixtures). In some regions, red can also be used as a hot wire.\n\n2. **Green**: This color is used for ground wires. Ground wires provide a safe pathway for electrical current to flow back to the ground in case of a fault, preventing electrical shock or fire hazards. In some systems, bare (uninsulated) wire can also serve as a ground.\n\n3. **Red**: This is often used as a second hot wire in 220-240 volt circuits, particularly in configurations where multiple phases are involved. It may also be used in switch legs or for specific applications where additional hot wires are needed.\n\nIn other regions, the wire colors may differ slightly. For example, in Europe, the standard colors are often brown for live, blue for neutral, and green/yellow stripes for ground. Always refer to local electrical codes and standards for the specific color conventions used in your area.",
